  "output": "Confirmed: no React/frontend framework here (just one static Jinja-style HTML template for CVs), so I'm grounding this in the actual stack — an async Python fetch/filter/dedup pipeline backed by SQLite.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-74` (real, highest-impact)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, sequentially, inside a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nWith sources like Amazon/Microsoft (`max_pages` up to 40 × 10/page = up to 400 rows each) and dozens of configured sources in `sources.yaml`, this is thousands of round-trip `SELECT`s per run, each paying SQLite's statement-parse/plan overhead.\n\n**Fix** — one query to pull all existing hashes, then batch the writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\").fetchall())\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(INSERT_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(UPDATE_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                     [(now, k) for k in touched])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) `SELECT`s into 1, and gives SQLite's `executemany` a single prepared statement to reuse for the writes instead of re-preparing per row.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (real, easy fix)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **on every job**, and `filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per fetched job:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFor a run pulling a few thousand listings, the same keyword list gets `re.compile`'d thousands of times.\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n## 3. Missing index — `store.py:111-119`\n\n`added_since()` (used by `agent.py db-new`, the scan entry point) does:\n\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\n```\n\nOnly `idx_jobs_company` exists (`store.py:27`) — there's no index on `first_seen`, so this is a full table scan + filesort on every scan as `jobs.db` grows.\n\n**Fix**: add `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);` to `_SCHEMA`.\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity — `fetchers.py:537-574` (Meta)\n\n`fetch_meta` re-scrapes the full `metacareers.com/jobs` HTML page every run just to extract the `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens (`fetchers.py:542-545`) before making the actual GraphQL POST. That's an unavoidable extra request today (tokens are short-lived), so there's nothing to cache within a single run — but it's worth knowing this doubles Meta's request count relative to every other source, which matters if `concurrency` (`pipeline.py:21`, default 8) is tuned tightly.\n\n## 5. Sequential pagination (inherent, not a bug, but worth flagging)\n\n`fetch_google`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver` (`fetchers.py`) all page with a `for page_n in range(max_pages): await ...` loop — each request waits on the last. This is correct (you don't know the total until you've paged), but it means a source with `max_pages=40` at 10/page pays 40 sequential round-trips serialized *within* that one source's slot in the `asyncio.Semaphore(concurrency)` (`fetchers.py:773`). Not a fix so much as a tuning note: since `fetch_all` already runs sources concurrently up to `concurrency`, the wall-clock cost is dominated by whichever single source has the most pages, not the sum — so this is fine as-is unless one board (e.g. Microsoft `max_pages=40`) becomes the long pole.\n\n## Not applicable here\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend framework in this repo — `templates/cv-template.html` is a static Jinja-style template rendered once per CV, not a component tree.\n- **Classic memory leaks**: this is a short-lived CLI process per invocation (`pipeline.run_sync`, `agent.py`), not a long-running server — there's no accumulating state across requests to leak. The one thing to watch is `httpx.AsyncClient` lifecycle in `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:770-787`), but it's already correctly closed in a `finally` when the function owns it.\n\n**Priority**: fix #1 (N+1 diff) and #2 (regex recompilation) first — both are real algorithmic waste that scales with job count and are cheap, low-risk changes. Want me to implement them?\n",
